The '''Georgina Basin''' is a large (c. 330,000&nbsp;km²) [[craton|intracratonic]] [[sedimentary basin]] in central and northern [[Australia]], lying mostly within the [[Northern Territory]] and partly within [[Queensland]].<ref>Smith, KG (1972). "Stratigraphy of the Georgina Basin." Bureau of Mineral Resources, Australia, Bulletin 111.</ref> It is named after the [[Georgina River]] which drains part of the basin. Deposition of locally up to c. 4&nbsp;km of marine and non-marine [[sedimentary rock]]s took place from the [[Neoproterozoic]] to the late [[Paleozoic]] (c. 850-350 [[Annum|Ma]]). Along with other nearby sedimentary basins of similar age ([[Amadeus Basin]], [[Officer Basin]]), the Georgina Basin is believed to have once been part of the hypothetical [[Centralian Superbasin]], that was fragmented during episodes of tectonic activity.
