'''Islamo-leftism''' ({{lang-fa|چپ اسلامی}}; {{lang-fr|islamo-gauchisme}}, {{lang-es|Islamo-izquierdismo}}),<ref name="HermosaIslamoIzquierdismo">{{cite news|last1=Hermosa|first1=Borja|title=Finkielkraut, contra el "neoprogresismo" y el "islamo-izquierdismo"|url=http://cultura.elpais.com/cultura/2017/01/26/actualidad/1485461021_814480.html|accessdate=28 March 2017|publisher=[[El País]]|date=26 January 2017}}</ref> adjectivally '''Islamo-leftist''' ({{lang-fr|islamo-gauchistes|links=no}});<ref name=Guibert>{{cite news|last1=Guibert|first1=Philippe|title=Il faut inventer la "politique musulmane" de la France|url=http://www.slate.fr/story/107855/compromis-musulmans-france-manent|accessdate=2 November 2015|publisher=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|date=7 October 2015}}</ref> is a neologism applied to the political alliance between [[Left-wing politics|leftists]] and [[Islamism|Islamists]].

==History of term==
Essays in ''[[Libération]]'' and [[France 24]] on the history of this term do not claim to find the definitive origin of this term, rather, both publications trace the term as far back as a 2002 use in ''New Judeophobia'', a book by [[Pierre-André Taguieff]], historian of ideas, who describes Islamo-fascism as a type of anti-Zionism popular among "the new third-worldist, neo-communist and neo-leftist configuration, better known as the 'anti-globalization movement.' "<ref name="FaureIslamoGauchisme">{{cite news|last1=Faure|first1=Sonya|title=Islamo-gauchisme, aux origines d'une expression médiatique|url=http://www.liberation.fr/debats/2016/04/14/islamo-gauchisme-aux-origines-d-une-expression-mediatique_1445857|accessdate=19 March 2017|publisher=Liberation|date=14 April 2016}}</ref><ref name="QuestcequecetIslamoGauchisme">{{cite news|title=Qu'est ce que cet "islamo-gauchisme" dont le camp Valls accuse Hamon ?|url=http://www.france24.com/fr/20170125-islamo-gauchisme-signification-manuel-valls-accuse-benoit-hamon-primaire|accessdate=28 March 2017|publisher=France 24|date=25 January 2017}}</ref> Interviewed in 2016 by ''Liberation'' journalists Sonya Faure and Frantz Durupt, Taguieff is not certain whether he coined it or had heard it used, but he points out that the phrases Islamo-Progressives, and, in the 1980s, palestino-progressives were used as self-descriptions by the French left.<ref name="FaureIslamoGauchisme"/>

According to [[Alain Badiou]] and Eric Hazan, Islamo-leftists was coined by French police for reasons of simple utility.<ref name="Alain Badiou">{{cite book|last1=[[Alain Badiou]], Eric Hazan|title="Anti-Semitism is Everywhere" in France Today, Chapter in, ''Reflections On Anti-Semitism''|date=2013|publisher=Verso Books|page=41}}</ref> [[Al Jazeera]] claims that the term Islamo-leftism was coined by [[Marine Le Pen]], who uses it "to describe what she considers an unhealthy alliance between "Islamist fanatics" and the [[French Left]]."<ref name=Ryan>{{cite news|last1=Ryan|first1=Yasmine|title=French right focuses on 'radical' Muslims|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2012/04/201244102955800772.html|accessdate=3 November 2015|publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]|date=6 April 2012}}</ref>

==Definitions==

French philosopher [[Pascal Bruckner]] understands Islamo-leftism as  "the fusion between the atheist Far Left and religious radicalism."<ref name=Bruckner>{{cite book|last1=Bruckner|first1=Pascal|title=The Tyranny of Guilt: An Essay on Western Masochism|date=2010|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1400834310|page=25|title-link=The Tyranny of Guilt}}</ref>  According to Bruckner, Islamo-leftism was "chiefly" conceived by British [[Trotskyism|Trotskyites]] of the [[Socialist Workers Party (UK)|Socialist Workers Party]].  Because these dedicated Leftists perceive Islam's potential for fomenting societal unrest, they promote tactical, temporary alliances with reactionary Muslim parties.  According to Bruckner, Leftist adherents of [[Third-Worldism]] hope to use [[Islamism]] as a "battering-ram" to bring about the downfall of free-market capitalism, and they see the sacrifice of individual rights  - in particular, of women's rights - as an acceptable trade-off in service of the greater goal of destroying capitalism.  Bruckner contends that [[Islamists]], for their part, pretend to join the left in its opposition to racism, [[neocolonialism]], and globalization as a tactical and temporary means to achieve their true goal of imposing the "totalitarian theocracy" of Islamist government.<ref name=Bruckner/><ref name=Pascal>{{cite news|last1=Pascal|first1=Julia|title=The Tyranny Of Guilt: An Essay On Western Masochism, By Pascal Bruckner, trans by Steven Rendall|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/the-tyranny-of-guilt-an-essay-on-western-masochism-by-pascal-bruckner-trans-by-steven-rendall-1951335.html|accessdate=2 November 2015|publisher=[[The Independent]]|date=22 September 2011}}</ref>

Political scientist Maurice Fraser regards Islamo-leftism as part of a, "striking and recent abdication of the Enlightenment project of human rights, freedom, secularism, science and progress," on the part of the political left, particularly among the anti-globalization activists of the New Left.<ref name=Fraser>{{cite journal|last1=Fraser|first1=Maurice|title=Is the Decline of the West Reversible?|journal=[[Wilfried Martens Centre for European Studies|European View]]|date=11 November 2010|volume=2|issue=2|page=149|doi=10.1007/s12290-010-0128-0}}</ref>

[[Bernard-Henri Lévy]] has described "Islamo-leftism" as, "this grand new alliance between the reds and the new [[Sturmabteilung|browns]], of the axis which runs from Le Monde diplomatique to the death squads,"<ref name="WaldenTwoIntellectuals">{{cite news|last1=[[George Walden]]|title=Public Enemies; Two French intellectuals fight it out.|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/books/2011/12/levy-houellebecq-french|accessdate=19 March 2017|publisher=[[New Statesman]]|date=5 December 2011}}</ref> and as a sort of "anti-American religion."<ref name="HenriLévy">{{cite book|last1=[[Bernard-Henri Lévy]]|title=Left in Dark Times: A Stand Against the New Barbarism|date=2009|publisher=Random House|isbn=978-0812974720|page=114}}</ref>

According to [[Mark Silinsky]] of the [[United States Army War College]], Islamo-leftism is alliance of Islamists and leftists in opposition to Western values that can also be also referred to as the "red-green axis."<ref name="Silinsky">{{cite book|last1=Silinsky|first1=Mark|title=Jihad and the West: Black Flag over Babylon|date=2016|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=978-0253027207|page=49|url=https://books.google.com/?id=kpZNDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA49&dq=%22islamo-leftism%22#v=onepage&q=%22islamo-leftism%22&f=false}}</ref>  Silinsky characterizes the black-green alliance between [[Black Lives Matter]] and the [[Council on American–Islamic Relations]] as an example of Islamo-leftism.<ref name="Silinsky"/>

According to [[Robert S. Wistrich]], "A poisonous anti-Jewish legacy can be found in Marx, Fourier, and Proudhon, extending through the orthodox Communists and "non-conformist" Trotskyists to the Islamo-Leftist hybrids of today who...  (are allied with) the [[Islamist]] anti-Semites of [[Hamas]].<ref name="WistrichBetrayal">{{cite book|last1=Robert|first1=Wistrich|title=From Ambivalence to Betrayal: The Left, the Jews, and Israel|date=2012|publisher=University of Nebraska Press|isbn=978-0803240834|page=xii|url=https://books.google.com/?id=yBvt4Fwc5XoC&pg=PR12&dq=%22islamo-leftist%22#v=onepage&q=%22islamo-leftist%22&f=false|accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref>

[[Alvin Hirsch Rosenfeld]] describes Islamo Leftism as, "the hope, entertained by a revolutionary fringe, of seeing Islam become the spearhead of a new insurrection, engaged in a 'Holy War against global capitalism."<ref name="RosenfeldDeciphering">{{cite book|last1=Rosenfeld|first1=Alvin|title=Deciphering the New Antisemitism|date=2015|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=978-0253018694|page=12|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ibfkCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA12&dq=%22islamo-leftism%22#v=onepage&q=%22islamo-leftism%22&f=false}}</ref>

=== "Islamo-leftism" in Iran ===
[[Shireen Hunter]] credits [[Mahmoud Taleghani]]'s reinterpretation of Islam in the light of Marxist theory in the 1970s with inspiring the "Islamo-leftist" group [[People's Mujahedin of Iran|Mujahaedin-e-Khalq]].<ref name="Hunter">{{cite book|last1=Hunter|first1=Shireen|title=Iran's Foreign Policy in the Post-Soviet Era: Resisting the New International Order|date=2010|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0313381942|page=27|url=https://books.google.com/?id=wLtA_J3VUt4C&pg=PA27&dq=%22islamo-leftist%22#v=onepage&q=%22islamo-leftist%22&f=false|accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref> According to Hunter, one of the goals of Islamo-leftism in the Muslim world during that period was to combat the Left by borrowing parts of its platform, thus hoping to attract economically disadvantaged groups like the [[Shia]] to Islamic politics. The result of these developments was the left-wing "radicalization of Islam" and "the emergence of what could be described as a leftist Islam."<ref name=HunterFuture>{{cite book|last1=[[Shireen Hunter]]|title=The Future of Islam and the West|date=1998|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0275962883|page=94}}</ref>  Hunter describes the way in which "Islamo-leftist intellectuals (the Mujahedin e Khalq) and Islamo-liberal intellectuals (the Islamic wing of the [[National Front (Iran)|National Front]] and later the [[Freedom Movement of Iran|Freedom Movement]]) also directed anti-Pahlavi activities," which included guerrilla warfare.<ref name="HunterVoices">{{cite book|title=Reformist Voices of Islam: Mediating Islam and Modernity|first=|date=2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1317461241|location=|page=|pages=42, 45|last1=[[Shireen Hunter]]}}</ref> Frictions later between the various Islamic groups that had participated in the [[Iranian Revolution]], with [[Morteza Motahhari]], a socially progressive ally of [[Ruhollah Khomeini|Khomeini]] being assassinated by an Islamo-leftist followers of [[Ali Shariati]].<ref name="HunterVoices" /> According to [[Olivier Roy (professor)|Olivier Roy]], the three major Iranian political groups — leftist, Islamist, and Islamo-leftist — active in the 1970s had revolutionary rather than liberal democratic ideologies.<ref name=Roy>{{cite book|last1=[[Olivier Roy (professor)|Olivier Roy]], chapter in book edited by Larry Diamond, Marc F. Plattner|title=Democratization and Authoritarianism in the Arab World|date=2014|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|isbn=978-1421414164|page=41}}</ref>

==Use in fiction==

In his 2015 novel, ''[[Submission (novel)|Submission]]'', [[Michel Houellebecq]] has Robert Rediger, the fictional character who is a convert to Islam and university professor turned politician, describe Islamo-leftism as "a desperate attempt by moldering, putrefying, brain-dead [[Marxism|Marxists]] to hoist themselves out of the [[ash heap of history|dustbin of history]] by latching onto the coattails of Islam."<ref name=Houellebecq>{{cite book|last1=Houellebecq|first1=Michel|title=Submission|date=2015|publisher=Farrar, Straus, Giroux|pages=223}}</ref><ref name="BrassHouellebecq">{{cite book|last1=Brass|first1=Tom|title=Labour Markets, Identities, Controversies: Reviews and Essays, 1982-2016|date=2017|publisher=Brill|isbn=978-9004337091|page=79|url=https://books.google.com/?id=dtvzDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA79&dq=Houellebecq++++%22islamo-leftism%22#v=onepage&q=Houellebecq%20%20%20%20%22islamo-leftism%22&f=false|accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref>

