{{South Korea national parks}}
The '''national parks of [[South Korea]]''' are preserved parcels of [[public land]] on which most forms of development are prohibited. They cover a total of 6.6% of the country's area, and are typically located in mountainous or coastal regions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.index.go.kr/egams/stts/jsp/potal/stts/PO_STTS_IdxMain.jsp?idx_cd=1460&bbs=INDX_001 |title= e-나라지표 국립공원현황|publisher= Statistics Korea|accessdate=2016-09-19|language=Korean}}</ref> The country's largest mountain park is [[Jirisan National Park]] in the southwest; this was also the first national park to be designated in 1967. The largest marine park is [[Dadohaehaesang National Park|Dadohaehaesang]], with an area of more than {{convert|2200|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}, but almost all of this is water. The smallest park is [[Wolchulsan National Park|Wolchulsan]], with an area of only {{convert|56.1|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}.

As of 2016, there are 22 national parks in South Korea; the parks, with the exception of [[Hallasan National Park]], are managed by the [[Korea National Park Service]], established in 1987.<ref name="knps.or.kr">{{cite web |url=http://english.knps.or.kr/AboutUs/NationalParks/Default.aspx?MenuNum=6&Submenu=NationalParks |title=National Parks: About the Korea National Park Service |author= |date= |work= |publisher=Korea National Park Service |accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref> The Authority operates its own police force, and since 1998 has been under the jurisdiction of the [[Ministry of Environment (South Korea)|Ministry of Environment]]. It was previously under the jurisdiction of the Ministry of Construction.

